# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mount-cook-national-park
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] It is Disney's second film adaptation of L'Engle's novel, following the 2003 television film.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Development began in late 2010, with Stockwell writing the first draft of the script, and Lee joining to rewrite it four years later.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] DuVernay signed on to direct in early 2016.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Principal photography began on November 2, 2016, in Los Angeles, California.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Near the end of filming, production moved to New Zealand, where photography ended on February 25, 2017.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] With an estimated production budget of $103 million, the film became the first $100-million-budget live-action film to be directed by an African-American woman.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Ramin Djawadi composed and conducted the film's score.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Thirteen-year-old Meg Murry struggles to adjust at school due to bullying and depression, four years after the disappearance of her father, Alex, who was a renowned astrophysicist.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Meg discovers her gifted younger brother, Charles Wallace, with an unusual visitor, Mrs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Whatsit, who claims that the tesseract — a method of space travel Alex was studying — is real.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Meg and Charles Wallace meet Calvin O'Keefe, who joins them at the house of Mrs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Who, another strange friend of Charles Wallace: she speaks only in quotations.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Calvin has dinner with the Murry family, and Mrs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Murry recalls Alex's commitment to their research despite public ridicule.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Which, revealing themselves as astral travelers.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Explaining that they have come to help find Alex (who did not leave his family, but has transported himself across the universe), the three Misses lead Meg, Calvin, and Charles Wallace through a tesseract to the distant planet Uriel.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] The planet's sentient flowers confirm that Alex visited Uriel.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Whatsit transforms into a leaf-like flying creature, and carries the children into the sky.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Calvin nearly falls to his death after noticing a dark planet that Mrs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Which identifies as Camazotz, home to evil energy known as "the IT".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] They tesser to the planet Orion to seek the help of a seer named Happy Medium.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Which reveals that the IT spreads negativity throughout the universe, including on Earth.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Happy Medium helps Meg overcome her self-doubt, and they learn that her father tessered to Uriel, then Ixchel, but was trapped on Camazotz.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] The Misses insist they regroup on Earth, but Meg's determination to save her father overrides the tesseract, unintentionally redirecting them to Camazotz.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Unable to stay (as Camazotz's evil is stronger than their light), the Misses bestow gifts before departing: Mrs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Who gives Meg her glasses to see what is really there, Mrs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Whatsit gives Meg the knowledge of her faults, and Mrs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Which gives the children the command to never separate.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] A forest appears, separating Meg and Calvin from Charles Wallace.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] They are pursued by a tornado-like storm; Meg uses the storm's own force to slingshot her and Calvin atop a cliff wall, where they reunite with Charles Wallace.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] They find themselves in a neighborhood of lookalike homes, children, and mothers; one woman invites the children inside.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Meg politely declines her offer, feeling suspicious.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Their surroundings transform into a crowded beach, where a man introduces himself as Red.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Assuring them that Alex is safe, he offers them food.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] When Charles Wallace says the food tastes like sand, Red possesses him through the IT, of which Red is actually a puppet.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Meg and Calvin chase after Red and Charles Wallace through the crowd, but are trapped in a seemingly empty, spherical room.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Red deactivates, while the possessed Charles Wallace taunts Meg and Calvin.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Who's glasses, Meg finds an invisible staircase to another room where her father is imprisoned.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] After a happy but tearful reunion, they are dragged away by Charles Wallace to meet his master.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] As Calvin and Meg fall under the IT's power, Alex opens a tesseract to escape with the two of them.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Refusing to abandon Charles Wallace, Meg projects back to Camazotz and confronts the IT in its malevolent, neuron-like form.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Charles Wallace and the IT try to force Meg to give in to darkness, menacing her with an idealized version of herself, but Meg embraces her own imperfections and uses her love for her brother to free him.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] The IT dissipates as the Misses reappear, congratulating Meg and Charles Wallace on becoming "Warriors of Light".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Meg tessers them home, where Alex is reunited with his wife.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Meanwhile, Calvin leaves to confront his father, and Meg looks to the sky, thanking the Misses.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] In October 2010, Walt Disney Pictures retained the film rights for the 1962 novel *A Wrinkle in Time*, by Madeleine L'Engle, which had previously been made as a 2003 television film.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Following the financial success of Tim Burton's *Alice in Wonderland* (2010), Disney hired Jeff Stockwell to write the screenplay for Cary Granat and his new Bedrock Studios.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Granat had previously worked with Disney on the *Chronicles of Narnia* and *Bridge to Terabithia* films.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] The project's budget was slated to be $35 million, which the company compared to *District 9* and *Bridge to Terabithia*, both of which were made for less than $30 million.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] However, *A Wrinkle in Time* was part of a new California Film Commission tax credit program, which offset production costs considerably.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] On August 5, 2014, Jennifer Lee was announced as the screenwriter, taking over from Stockwell, who wrote the first draft.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] On February 8, 2016, it was reported that Ava DuVernay had been offered the job of directing the film, and she was confirmed to direct later that same month.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] She became the first African-American woman to direct a live-action film with a production budget of more than $100 million.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] The decision received positive sentiments in the media industry.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Oprah Winfrey was happy to see this because DuVernay herself broke barriers for non-white people in the film industry.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Irene Monroe of *The Cambridge Day* expressed her feelings that Ava DuVernay was a superb choice of a director because she was able to highlight and expose the struggles experienced by young African-American girls.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] On July 26, 2016, *Variety* reported that Oprah Winfrey began final negotiations to join the film to play Mrs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Ws, celestial beings who guide the children along their journey.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] In September, 2016, Reese Witherspoon and Mindy Kaling were reported to be in talks to join the film, with Witherspoon to play Mrs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Whatsit, a chatty, grandmotherly sprite, and Kaling to play the quotation-reciting Mrs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] On September 13, 2016, Storm Reid was cast in the lead role of Meg Murry, a young girl traumatized by the disappearance of her scientist father years before.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] In October 2016, Gugu Mbatha-Raw and Chris Pine were cast as Meg's parents, Drs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] On November 1, 2016, additional cast announcements included Zach Galifianakis as Happy Medium, André Holland as Principal Jenkins, Levi Miller as Calvin, and Deric McCabe as Charles Wallace, along with Bellamy Young, Rowan Blanchard and Will McCormack.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Later, Michael Peña joined the cast to play Red.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] The film producers are James Whitaker and Catherine Hand.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Principal photography on the film began November 2, 2016, in Los Angeles, California.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Schliessler was the film's cinematographer, Naomi Shohan was production designer, Paco Delgado was costume designer, and Rich McBride was the film's visual effects supervisor.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] During production, DuVernay asked McBride to be as flexible as possible on visual effects sequences to enable her to make changes and incorporate new ideas during shooting.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Filming for *A Wrinkle in Time* took place in multiple locations including Eureka, California, in Humboldt County, starting November 29, 2016.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] After Los Angeles, production moved to New Zealand for two weeks.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] During the last two weeks of February 2017, filming locations for *A Wrinkle in Time* were in Central Otago, New Zealand.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Actors and crew were in New Zealand for two weeks to shoot scenes in the Southern Alps, including at Hunter Valley Station near Lake Hāwea, with cast and crew treated to a traditional Māori pōwhiri and karakia.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Filming wrapped up in New Zealand's South Island after two weeks, and DuVernay declared the cast and crew's love for New Zealand in an Instagram post.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] On September 28, 2017, Ramin Djawadi was announced as the composer for the film, replacing Jonny Greenwood, who was initially chosen to compose and score the film.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] On February 20, 2018, it was announced that the soundtrack would feature appearances from Sade, Sia, Kehlani, Chloe x Halle, Freestyle Fellowship, DJ Khaled, and Demi Lovato.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] In the U.S. and Canada, *A Wrinkle in Time* was released alongside *The Hurricane Heist*, *Gringo*, and *The Strangers: Prey at Night*, and was projected to gross $30–38 million from 3,980 theaters in its opening weekend.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] It made $10.2 million on its first day, including $1.3 million from Thursday night previews.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] It went on to debut at $33.1 million, finishing second behind Disney's own *Black Panther* ($41.1 million in its fourth weekend).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] In its second weekend, the film made $16.6 million, dropping 50% to fourth place.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] On June 15, in its 15th week of release, the film returned to a total of 245 theaters, often as part of a double feature with *Incredibles 2* at drive-in theaters, where the box-office revenue was credited equally to both films.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] It ended up making $1.7 million (a 1,600% increase from the previous weekend), pushing the total U.S. gross to $100 million.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Internationally, the film opened in six countries alongside the U.S. and grossed $6.3 million in its opening weekend, with Russia being the largest market with $4.1 million.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] On Rotten Tomatoes, the film holds an approval rating of 43% based on 342 reviews, and an average rating of 5.3/10.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Audiences polled by CinemaScore gave the film an average grade of "B" on an A+ to F scale, while PostTrak reported filmgoers gave it a 75% overall positive score; audience members under age 18 gave it an average grade of "A−" and a positive score of 89%.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Kat Candler, an American independent filmmaker, stated that the film was a "gorgeous love letter to the warriors of the next generation".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Mercedes Howze of the *New Pittsburgh Courier* stated that the visuals were extraordinary and that the film "continues to make lasting impressions on innocent minds to change what it looks like to be a young black woman".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Vince Mancini of *Uproxx* gave the film a negative review, saying, "...if anything, the trouble with *Wrinkle* is that you never really get a sense of DuVernay's personal touch.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] In fact, it feels a lot like Brad Bird's big-budget, equally smarmy 2015 Disney film *Tomorrowland*.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Both attempt to be so broad and universal that they feel disconnected from anything human.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Todd McCarthy of *The Hollywood Reporter* felt that the film was "unable to charm or disarm" the audience.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] Wenlei Ma, film and TV critic of *news.com.au,* stated that, following the halfway mark in the film, movie-goers find themselves "not caring about the other characters besides Meg" and that it seemed to "drag" in the latter half.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/a-wrinkle-in-time-2018-film] She called the film a disappointment, regardless of the value parents find in the messages for children via quotations from Mahatma Gandhi and Nelson Mandela.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area of the park has seen human interaction for approximately 700 years, with evidence of habitation dating back to early Māori iwi such as Waitaha and Rapuwai during the early periods of Māori habitation in New Zealand.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Following the arrival of Pākehā in the 19th century, the area saw widespread deforestation, farming, and quarrying, significantly modifying the area's environment.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this, the park is one of the most modified landscapes of any of New Zealand's national parks, with management of the park largely focusing on regeneration and restoration of the traditional ecosystem.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was first established in 1942 to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's 1642 visit in New Zealand, when he became the first European to sight the islands.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It has since been progressively expanded from its original borders, the most recent of which involved the addition of 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet after a successful crowdfunding campaign.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The coastal area was inhabited for hundreds of years by Māori prior to the arrival of Europeans, with sites throughout the area occupied both seasonally and permanently.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In addition to harvesting food from the local forests, estuaries and waters, locals grew kūmara.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Historical records indicate a pā was established at Auckland Point by Pohea, who travelled there around 1450 from the Whanganui area.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] From the mid-1500s Muaūpoko (formerly known as Ngāi Tara) occupied the area until the early 1600s, when they were ousted by Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri were present when Abel Tasman reached Golden Bay / Mohua in 1642.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was founded in 1942, largely through the efforts of ornithologist and author Pérrine Moncrieff to have land reserved for the purpose.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Moncrieff served on the park board from 1943 to 1974.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was opened on 18 December 1942 to mark the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's visit.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Those in attendance at the opening ceremony at Tarakohe included Charles van der Plas, as personal representative of the Netherlands' Queen, Wilhelmina.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The idea for the park had been under consideration since June 1938.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Crown set aside 15,225 hectares (37,622 acres), comprising 8,900 hectares (21,900 acres) of proposed state forest, 5,809 hectares (14,354 acres) of Crown land and 554 hectares (1,368 acres) of other reserve land for the national park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Golden Bay Cement Company donated the land where the Abel Tasman Monument and a memorial plaque was sited.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area's primary historic interest was the visit of Tasman in 1642, D'Urville in 1827, and the New Zealand Company barques *Whitby* and *Will Watch*, and brig *Arrow* in 1841.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The site was also of significant botanical interest.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] By 1946 the park had reached 15,534 hectares (38,386 acres) in area with additional land purchases.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] A further 844 hectares (2,085 acres) at Tōtaranui, formerly owned by William Gibbs, was acquired from J S Campbell in 1949 and added to the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] About 6,100 hectares (15,000 acres) have been added since.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2008 an extra 7.9 km2 (790 ha; 3.1 sq mi), including the formerly private land known as Hadfields Clearing, were added to the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2016, a further 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet was purchased by New Zealanders in a crowdfunding campaign.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Covering an area of 237 km2 (92 sq mi; 59,000 acres), the park is the smallest of New Zealand's national parks.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It consists of forested, hilly country to the north of the valleys of the Tākaka and Riwaka Rivers, and is bounded to the north by the waters of Golden Bay / Mohua and Tasman Bay.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains some of the islands off the coast including the Tata Islands in Golden Bay / Mohua, and Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island, and Fisherman Island in Tasman Bay.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park does not extend beyond Mean High Water Mark on the adjacent coast.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Between Mean High Water and Mean Low Water Springs, the beaches are gazetted as a Scenic Reserve, covering 7.74 km2 (2.99 sq mi) in total.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Tonga Island Marine Reserve adjoins part of the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Monument, though not located in the park, commemorates the first contact between Europeans and Māori and is located near the northern end of the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Abel Tasman National Park stands out from most other National parks of New Zealand, given that a large area of it has undergone extensive environmental modification in its history.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Early European settlers burned or cleared much of the forest, only to find that the soil was unsuitable for farming.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This practise not only destroyed much of the shrubland and forests, but also introduced invasive plants found throughout the modern-day park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] However, as time progresses, the original ecosystems and forests are slowly returning.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains varied habitats, including coastal forests, sub-alpine bogs, and sand dunes.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this diversity, many different species can be found.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The islands of the park, in particular Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island and Fisherman Island which are the largest, have been disturbed less and have no introduced mammalian predators.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result the islands have species not found elsewhere in the park and there are more restrictions to visitor access.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Though much of the parkland is pasture or covered with shrubs, valley areas contain forests of rātā, mataī, miro and hinau.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Over 70 species of birds have been recorded in the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Some of the birds that can frequently be seen are petrels, shags, penguins, gulls, terns, and herons.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Possums, wild pigs, deer, and goats can also be seen in the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Coast Track is a popular tramping track that follows the coastline and is one of the Department of Conservation's Great Walks; the Abel Tasman Inland Track is less frequented.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Other walks in the park, such as the Wainui Falls Track are considered "short walks".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Kayaking, camping and sightseeing are other activities.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Access to the park is usually via the small settlement of Mārahau or Kaiteriteri (by water taxi).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The nearest large town is Motueka, 20 kilometres (12 mi) to the south.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Dogs (excepting guide dogs) are not allowed in the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation administers the National Park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Scenic Reserve is administered by the Tasman District Council Chief Executive and Department of Conservation's Nelson / Marlborough Conservator.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Activities in adjoining coastal waters are Tasman District Council's responsibility.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] These areas operate under separate regulations.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Interior, consisting of the park areas further inland.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Park plans include ecological surveys, pest control, and protection of heritage areas and caves.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Islands, encompassing all islands within the park, some of which are closed to the public. key priorities include keeping them free of invasive pests, reintroducing native species, and minimizing human impacts.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2012 Project Janszoon, a privately funded trust, was set up to restore the park's ecosystems.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The trust takes its name from Tasman's middle name *Janszoon*.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It is aiming to complete the restoration in time for the 400th anniversary of Tasman's visit and the park's 100th anniversary in 2042.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation and Project Janszoon developed a free virtual visitor centre for downloading to smartphones or tablets.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The application provides information about the Park's history, its flora and fauna, points of interest, weather, walking tracks, and tides.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This virtual visitor centre is free of charge and can be found through the App Store or Google Play Store.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Likely born in 1602 or 1603 in Lutjegast, Netherlands, Tasman started his career as a merchant seaman and became a skilled navigator.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In 1633, he joined the VOC and sailed to Batavia, now Jakarta, Indonesia.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He participated in several voyages, including one to Japan.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In 1642, Tasman was appointed by the VOC to lead an expedition to explore the uncharted regions of the Southern Pacific Ocean.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] His mission was to discover new trade routes and to establish trade relations with the native inhabitants.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] After leaving Batavia, Tasman sailed westward to Mauritius, then south to the Roaring Forties, then eastward, and reached the coast of Tasmania, which he named Van Diemen's Land after his patron, Anthony van Diemen.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He then sailed north east, and was the first European to discover the west coast of New Zealand, which he named *Staten Landt*.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] It was later renamed *Nieuw Zeeland*, after the Dutch province of Zeeland, by Joan Blaeu, official Dutch cartographer to the Dutch East India Company.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Despite his achievements, Tasman's expedition was not entirely successful.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The encounter with the Māori people on the South Island of New Zealand resulted in a violent confrontation, which left four of Tasman's men dead.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He returned to Batavia without having made any significant contact with the native inhabitants or establishing any trade relations.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman continued to serve the Dutch East India Company until his death in 1659.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] More than a century later, knowledge from Tasman's expeditions was used by James Cook, leading to exploration and colonization of Australia and New Zealand by the British.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Abel Tasman was likely born in 1602 or 1603 in Lutjegast, a village in the Province of Groningen.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He married Claesgie Heyndrix, with whom he had a daughter named Claesjen.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] A proclamation of his second marriage, given in December 1631 at Amsterdam, describes him as a widower and sailor.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] On 27 December 1631 as a 28-year old seafarer living in Amsterdam, he married 21-year-old Jannetje Tjaers, of Palmstraat in Amsterdam.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Uneducated, but employed by the Dutch East India Company (VOC), Tasman learned navigation and seamanship on the job.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In 1634, he was appointed skipper of the *Mocha*, and, under the command of Frans Valck, he went on a two-year voyage to the Maluku Islands.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In 1633, Tasman sailed from Texel in the Netherlands to Batavia (now Jakarta), using the southern Brouwer Route.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] While based in Batavia, he later joined a voyage to Seram Island, in what is now Indonesia’s Maluku Province.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The expedition was sent after local traders sold spices to European merchants other than the Dutch.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman docked to find wood for repairs and was separated from the other ships; a fight broke out with local villagers and at least two of Tasman's men were killed.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] By August 1637, Tasman had returned to Amsterdam, and in 1638 he signed on for another ten years and took his wife with him to Batavia via a six-month journey.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] On 25 March 1638, he tried to sell his property in the Jordaan, but the purchase was cancelled.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He was second-in-command of a 1639 expedition of exploration into the north Pacific under Matthijs Quast.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The fleet included the ships *Engel* and *Gracht* and reached Fort Zeelandia (Dutch Formosa) and Deshima (an artificial island off Nagasaki, Japan).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] One of the objectives was to obtain knowledge of "all the totally unknown" Provinces of Beach.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] This was a purported yet phantom island said to have plentiful gold, which had appeared on European maps since the 15th century, as a result of an error in some editions of Marco Polo's works.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The expedition was to use two small ships, *Heemskerck* and *Zeehaen*.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman sailed from Batavia on 14 August 1642 and reached Mauritius 22 days later, on 5 September 1642, according to the captain's journal.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] On the island there was fresh water, timber for repairs, and the crew could be well fed.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman also received assistance from the governor, Adriaan van der Stel.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Mauritius was chosen as a turning point because of the prevailing winds.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] After staying just over four weeks, the two ships, *Heemskerck* and *Zeehaen*, left on 8 October and entered the Roaring Forties to make a fast eastward crossing.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] At the time, no expedition had sailed this far east.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Pieter Nuyts had come closest, reaching a similar point about 15 years earlier, in 1626–27.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] On 7 November, nearly a month into the crossing, snow and hail forced the ship's council to change course to the north-east, aiming instead for the Solomon Islands.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] On 24 November 1642, Tasman reached and sighted the west coast of Tasmania, north of Macquarie Harbour.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He named his discovery Van Diemen's Land, after Antonio van Diemen, Governor-General of the Dutch East Indies.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He tried to work his two ships into Adventure Bay on the east coast of South Bruny Island, but he was blown out to sea by a storm.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Two days later, on 1 December, Tasman anchored to the north of Cape Frederick Hendrick just north of the Forestier Peninsula.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] On 2 December, two ship's boats under the command of the Pilot, Major Visscher, rowed through the Marion Narrows into Blackman Bay, and then west to the outflow of Boomer Creek where they gathered some edible "greens".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman named the bay, Frederick Hendrik Bay, which included the present North Bay, Marion Bay and what is now Blackman Bay.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] (Tasman's original naming, Frederick Henrick Bay, was mistakenly transferred to its present location by Marion Dufresne in 1772).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman formally claimed the land on 3 December 1642.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] For two more days, he continued to follow the east coast northward to see how far it went.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] When the land veered to the north-west at Eddystone Point, he tried to follow the coast line but his ships were suddenly hit by the Roaring Forties howling through Bass Strait.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman was on a mission to find the Southern Continent not more islands, so he abruptly turned away to the east and continued his continent-hunting.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The expedition endured a rough voyage and in one of his diary entries Tasman claimed that his compass was the only thing that had kept him alive.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] On 13 December 1642 Tasman and his crew became the first Europeans to reach New Zealand when they sighted the north-west coast of the South Island.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman named it *Staten Landt* "in honour of the States General" (Dutch parliament).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He wrote, "it is possible that this land joins to the Staten Landt but it is uncertain", referring to Isla de los Estados, a landmass of the same name at the southern tip of South America, encountered by the Dutch navigator Jacob Le Maire in 1616.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] However, in 1643 Brouwer's expedition to Valdivia found out that Staaten Landt was separated by sea from the hypothetical Southern Land.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman continued: "We believe that this is the mainland coast of the unknown Southland." Tasman thought he had found the western side of the long-imagined *Terra Australis* that stretched across the Pacific to near the southern tip of South America.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] On 14 December 1642 Tasman's ships anchored 7 km offshore c.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] 20km south of Cape Foulwind near Greymouth.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The ships were observed by Māori who named a place on this coast Tiropahi (the place were a large sailing ship was seen).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] After sailing north then east for five days, the expedition anchored about 7 kilometres (4.3 mi) from the coast off what is now Golden Bay.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] A group of Māori paddled out in a waka (canoe) and attacked some sailors who were rowing between the two Dutch vessels.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Four sailors were clubbed to death with patu.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] As Tasman sailed out of the bay he observed 22 waka near the shore, of which "eleven swarming with people came off towards us".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The waka approached the *Zeehaen* which fired and hit a man in the largest waka holding a small white flag.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Canister shot also hit the side of a waka.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Archaeologist Ian Barber suggests that local Māori were trying to secure a cultivation field under ritual protection (tapu) where they believed the Dutch were attempting to land.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] December was at the mid-point of the locally important sweet potato/kūmara (*Ipomoea batatas*) growing season.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The expedition then sailed north, sighting Cook Strait, which separates the North and South Islands of New Zealand, and which it mistook for a bight and named "Zeehaen's Bight".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Two names that the expedition gave to landmarks in the far north of New Zealand still endure: Cape Maria van Diemen and Three Kings Islands.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] En route back to Batavia, Tasman came across the Tongan archipelago on 20 January 1643.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] While passing the Fiji Islands Tasman's ships came close to being wrecked on the dangerous reefs of the north-eastern part of the Fiji group.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He charted the eastern tip of Vanua Levu and Cikobia-i-Lau before making his way back into the open sea.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The expedition turned north-west towards New Guinea and arrived back in Batavia on 15 June 1643.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman left Batavia on 30 January 1644 on his second voyage with three ships: *Limmen*, *Zeemeeuw* and the tender *Braek*.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He followed the south coast of New Guinea eastwards in an attempt to find a passage to the eastern side of New Holland.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] However, he missed the Torres Strait between New Guinea and Australia and continued his voyage by following the shore of the Gulf of Carpentaria westwards along the north Australian coast.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He mapped the north coast of Australia, making observations on New Holland and its people.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He arrived back in Batavia about seven months later, in August 1644.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] From the point of view of the Dutch East India Company, Tasman's explorations were a disappointment: he had neither found a promising area for trade nor a useful new shipping route.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Although Tasman was received courteously on his return, the company was upset that Tasman had not fully explored the lands he found, and decided that a more "persistent explorer" should be chosen for any future expeditions.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] For over a century, until the era of James Cook, Tasmania and New Zealand were not visited by Europeans; mainland Australia was visited, but usually only by accident.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] On 2 November 1644, Abel Tasman was appointed a member of the Council of Justice in Batavia.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] He retired in 1653 at age fifty; at that time he owned 288 acres of land in Batavia and captained a small cargo ship, of which he was a part-owner.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In April 1657, Tasman wrote his will and testament, describing himself as ill but not bedridden.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman died at Batavia on 10 October 1659 at about age 56 and was survived by his second wife and a daughter by his first wife.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] His property was divided between his wife and his daughter.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In his will, he left 25 guilders to the poor of his village, Lutjegast.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Although Tasman's pilot, Frans Visscher, published *Memoir concerning the discovery of the South land* in 1642, Tasman's detailed journal was not published until 1898.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Nevertheless, some of his charts and maps were in general circulation and used by subsequent explorers.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The journal signed by Abel Tasman of the 1642 voyage is held in the Dutch National Archives at The Hague.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman's ten-month voyage in 1642–43 had significant consequences.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] By circumnavigating Australia (albeit at a distance) Tasman proved that the small fifth continent was not joined to any larger sixth continent, such as the long-imagined Southern Continent.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Further, Tasman's suggestion that New Zealand was the western side of that Southern Continent was seized upon by many European cartographers who, for the next century, depicted New Zealand as the west coast of a *Terra Australis* rising gradually from the waters around Tierra del Fuego.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] This theory was eventually disproved when Captain Cook circumnavigated New Zealand in 1769.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] His portrait has been on four New Zealand postage stamp issues, on a 1992 5 NZD coin, and on 1963, 1966 and 1985 Australian postage stamps.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In the Netherlands, many streets are named after him.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In Lutjegast, the village where he was born, there is a museum dedicated to his life and travels.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Tasman's life was dramatised for radio in *Early in the Morning* (1946) a play by Ruth Park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] A drawing titled *Abel Janssen Tasman, Navigateur en Australie* is held by the State Library of New South Wales as part of "a portfolio of 26 ink drawings of 16th and 17th century Dutch admirals, navigators and governor-generals of the VOC".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The portfolio was acquired at an art auction in The Hague in 1862.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] However, it is unclear if the drawing is of Tasman and its original source is unknown, although it has been said to resemble the work of Dutch engraver Jacobus Houbraken.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The drawing has been assessed as having the "most reliable provenance" of any depiction of Tasman with "no strong reason to doubt that the drawing is not genuine".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In 1948, the National Library of Australia acquired from Rex Nan Kivell a portrait purporting to depict Tasman with his wife and stepdaughter, which was attributed to Jacob Gerritsz.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In 2018 the painting was exhibited by the Groninger Museum in the Netherlands which identified it as "the only known portrait of the explorer".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] However, the Netherlands Institute for Art History has instead attributed the painting to Dirck van Santvoort and concluded that the painting does not depict Tasman and his family.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The provenance provided from Nan Kivell for the family portrait has been unable to be verified.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Nan Kivell claimed that the portrait was passed down through the Springer family – relatives of Tasman's widow – and was sold at Christie's in 1877.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] However, Christie's records indicate that the portrait was not owned by the Springer family or associated with Tasman, and was instead sold as "Portrait of an astronomer" by "Anthonie Palamedes" [sic].
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Nan Kivell additionally claimed that the portrait was sold at Christie's a second time in 1941, however no records exist to support this.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] A survey of portraits of Tasman published in 2019 concluded that the provenance was "either invented by Rex Nan Kivell or by the unnamed art dealer who sold it to Rex Nan Kivell", and that the painting "should therefore not be considered a portrait of Abel Tasman's family".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Outside of the Nan Kivell painting, another purported portrait of Tasman was "discovered" in 1893 and eventually acquired by the Tasmanian government in 1976 for the Tasmanian Museum and Art Gallery (TMAG).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The painting is unsigned and was attributed to Bartholomeus van der Helst at the time of its discovery, but this attribution was disputed by Dutch art historian Cornelis Hofstede de Groot and Alec Martin of Christie's.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In 1985, TMAG curator Dan Gregg stated that "the painter of the life-sized portrait is unknown [...] there is some uncertainty as to whether the portrait is really of Tasman".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Held within the collection of the State Library of New South Wales is the Tasman map, thought to have been drawn by Isaac Gilsemans, or completed under the supervision of Franz Jacobszoon Visscher.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The map is also known as the Bonaparte map, as it was once owned by Prince Roland Bonaparte, the great-nephew of Napoleon.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The map was completed sometime after 1644 and is based on the original charts drawn during Tasman's first and second voyages.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] As none of the journals or logs composed during Tasman's second voyage have survived, the Bonaparte map remains an important contemporary artefact of Tasman's voyage to the northern coast of the Australian continent.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The Tasman map reveals the extent of understanding the Dutch had of the Australian continent at the time.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The map includes the western and southern coasts of Australia, accidentally encountered by Dutch voyagers as they journeyed by way of the Cape of Good Hope to the VOC headquarters in Batavia.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In addition, the map shows the tracks of Tasman's two voyages.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Of his second voyage, the map shows the Banda Islands, the southern coast of New Guinea and much of the northern coast of Australia.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] However, the land areas adjacent to the Torres Strait are shown unexamined; this is despite Tasman having been given orders by VOC Council at Batavia to explore the possibility of a channel between New Guinea and the Australian continent.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] There is debate as to the origin of the map.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] It is widely believed that the map was produced in Batavia; however, it has also been argued that the map was produced in Amsterdam.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The authorship of the map has also been debated: while the map is commonly attributed to Tasman, it is now thought to have been the result of a collaboration, probably involving Franchoijs Visscher and Isaack Gilsemans, who took part in both of Tasman's voyages.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] Whether the map was produced in 1644 is also subject to debate, as a VOC company report in December 1644 suggested that at that time no maps showing Tasman's voyages were yet complete.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] In 1943, a mosaic version of the map, composed of coloured brass and marble, was inlaid into the vestibule floor of the Mitchell Library in Sydney.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/abel-tasman] The work was commissioned by the Principal Librarian William Ifould, and completed by the Melocco Brothers of Annandale, who also worked on the ANZAC War Memorial in Hyde Park and the crypt at St Mary's Cathedral, Sydney.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] This species was first described in 1956 by the New Zealand botanist Walter Oliver.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] The type locality of this species is Swampy Hill in Otago and the several syntype specimens, collected by Oliver on 25 November 1950, are held at Te Papa.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] The species epithet *aurea* refers to the distinctive golden colour of the plant.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] Plants are yellow-green, tufted herbs up to 1.5 m high (when in flower or fruit) with spiky rosettes up to 1 m diameter, and dioecious (with separate male and female plants).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] Leaves are up to 70 cm long, once- or twice-pinnately compound, petiolate, with thick, wide sheaths and stiff, sharp, tapering stipules up to 27 cm long.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] Petioles are up to 20 cm long and 16 mm wide and serrulate.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] Pinnae in 1–2 pairs, about 20 cm long, erect, serrulate.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] Stems are thick, ribbed, bracted, and tapering, up to 80 cm long with acicular stipules up to 8 cm long.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] Flowers are cream to yellow in colour, and grouped into compound inflorescences called umbels that have linear bracts.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] In male plants, the umbels are found along the length of the peduncles, which are longer than the umbel rays.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] In female plants, the umbels are on peduncles up to 15 cm long and are made up of umbellules on short rays.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] Seeds usually dark brown (sometimes golden brown), 5–7 mm long.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] Flowering is irregular and infrequent (every 3–4 years).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] Populations of *A. aurea* in the northern South Island (Marlborough and Nelson regions) show some characteristics that are different from the rest of the population, including golden brown seeds (rather than dark brown).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] Moa were once the main browser of this species: although the adult leaves have long spines to deter browsing by birds, young leaves are soft and flexible.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] These young leaves are also vulnerable to browsing by rabbits and hares.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/aciphylla-aurea] In experimental plots that has been fenced for 30 years to exclude these lagomorphs, young *Aciphylla aurea* plants were 15 times as abundant as in nearby plots where only cattle and sheep were excluded; adult plants were 7 times as abundant.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] An **active fault** is a fault that is likely to become the source of another earthquake sometime in the future.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Geologists commonly consider faults to be active if there has been movement observed or evidence of seismic activity during the last 10,000 years.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Active faulting is considered to be a geologic hazard – one related to earthquakes as a cause.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Effects of movement on an active fault include strong ground motion, surface faulting, tectonic deformation, landslides and rockfalls, liquefaction, tsunamis, and seiches.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Quaternary faults are those active faults that have been recognized at the surface and which have evidence of movement during the Quaternary Period.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Related geological disciplines for *active-fault* studies include geomorphology, seismology, reflection seismology, plate tectonics, geodetics and remote sensing, risk analysis, and others.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Active faults tend to occur in the vicinity of tectonic plate boundaries, and active fault research has focused on these regions.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Active faults tend to occur less within the area of any given plate.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] The fact that intraplate regions may also present seismic hazards has only recently been recognized.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Various geologic methods are used to define the boundaries of an active fault such as remote sensing and magnetic measurements, as well as other ways.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Several types of data, such as seismologic reports or records over time, are used to gauge fault activity.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Activity and fault area are correlated, and risk analysis is employed with other factors to determine the potential earthquake hazard.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] The geologic conditions and tectonic setting in much of the Western U.S. has resulted in the region being underlain by relatively thin crust and having high heat flow, both of which can favor relatively high deformation rates and active faulting.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] In contrast, in the Central and Eastern U.S.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] (CEUS) the crust is thicker, colder, older, and more stable.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Furthermore, the CEUS is thousands of miles from active plate boundaries, so the rates of deformation are low in this region.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/active-fault] Nevertheless, the CEUS has had some rather large earthquakes in historical times, including a series of major earthquakes near New Madrid, Missouri in 1811–1812, a large earthquake near Charleston, South Carolina in 1886, and the Cape Ann earthquake northeast of Boston in 1755.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The mountains, forests, tussock lands and river valleys are used for tramping, fishing kayaking, horse riding and hunting.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Both the park and neighbouring Ben Avon Station are located near the Aoraki Mackenzie International Dark Sky Reserve, a dark-sky preserve, and are used for astronomy.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The town is serviced by the tourist town of Omarama.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The park was established in 2005, and includes the Birchwood Station leasehold farm the New Zealand Government bought back for NZ$10 million in 2004.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] It contained extensive wetlands that had remained largely undeveloped.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Birchwood Station continued normal farming operations until the end of the leasehold in 2010.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The road to the former Birchwood Station homestead stopped being regularly maintained by Waitaki District Council in 2011.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] In 2014, ecologist Peter Espie reported a decrease in native plant species in the park, and suggested introducing grazing management.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Parts of the 2020 Disney film *Mulan* were filmed in the Ahuriri Valley near the conservation park, including the training camp scenes and some battle scenes.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] At the end of the most recent ice age approximately 13000 years ago, numerous glaciers in the park were tributaries of a much larger glacier covering all of Hooker Valley and Tasman Valley in hundreds of metres of ice.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] This glacier reached beyond the southern end of today's Lake Pukaki, up to 40 km (25 mi) south of Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] As it retreated, it filled the hollowed-out valleys, leaving behind the U-shaped valleys seen today in the national park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Early European surveyors and explorers ventured into the alpine region surrounding Aoraki / Mount Cook from the 1850s.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Many of the geographical features in the national park were named by or after them.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Ngāi Tahu Claims Settlement Act passed in October 1998 recognised the original names of some geographical features, establishing dual English / Māori names.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park is home to more than four hundred species of plants, including more than one hundred introduced species.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] There are about thirty-five species of birds in the park, most notably the rare black stilt and pīwauwau.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The only road access into the park is via State Highway 80 which starts 65 km (40 mi) away near Twizel, the closest town, and leads directly to Mount Cook Village along the western shore of Lake Pukaki.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Mount Cook Aerodrome is a small airfield located 5 km (3.1 mi) southeast of Mount Cook Village within the national park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park is a popular tourist destination.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] There are numerous walking tracks, the most popular being the Hooker Valley Track, a relatively short track that takes around three hours to complete.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park is also popular with astrophotographers and star-gazers because of the low levels of light pollution.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] An area including Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park and the Mackenzie Basin was designated as the Aoraki Mackenzie International Dark Sky Reserve in June 2012.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The national park has been used as a filming location for numerous films.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In Māori mythology, Aoraki was one of the sons of Raki the Sky Father.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] One version of the legend states that Aoraki came down from heaven in a canoe with three of his brothers, Rakiroa, Rakirua and Rārakiroa, to visit his father Raki's new wife Papatūānuku, but the *waka* (canoe) overturned.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The brothers climbed on to the overturned canoe, becoming the mountains Aoraki / Mount Cook, Rakiroa (Mount Dampier), Rakirua (Mount Teichelmann) and Rārakiroa (Mount Tasman).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The *waka* itself became the Southern Alps (*Kā Tiritiri o te Moana*).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Although there is no evidence of permanent or temporary Māori settlement within the national park, some artefacts and evidence of burnt vegetation have been found in the nearby Mackenzie Basin.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] These may be related to nomadic parties who would spend months here hunting moa or fighting other parties.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Māori would burn tōtara forests to assist them with their hunting of moa and gathering food, mostly weka, eels and kiore, before heading to the West Coast in search of *pounamu*.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1896, mountaineer Arthur Harper wrote that Māori had a deep-seated fear of the mountains and preferred to stay lower down in the valleys.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] However, Māori did have knowledge of the various features of high alpine areas, with special words for different types of ice and snow.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Historian Johannes Carl Andersen believed it was possible that Māori had travelled over the Main Divide, which is at the northern boundary of Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park, to trade *pounamu*.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] According to log entries made by explorer Abel Tasman, it is likely that he and his crew sighted the Southern Alps in December 1642 from the Tasman Sea near Barrytown.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1770 Captain James Cook sailed along the West Coast of the South Island.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] He sighted and named the Southern Alps but probably did not sight Aoraki.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki was given the name Mount Cook by Captain Stokes of the survey ship HMS *Acheron* in 1851, to honour James Cook's circumnavigation of New Zealand.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1998, the Ngāi Tahu Claims Settlement Act officially recognised the original names of the geographical features of Ngāi Tahu's *takiwā* (tribal area), establishing dual English and Māori names such as Kirikirikatata / Mount Cook Range and Haupapa / Tasman Glacier.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Europeans have had interest in the national park since the 1850s; public appreciation of the alpine regions surrounding Aoraki / Mount Cook grew with the maps and reports produced by early European surveyors and explorers.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Julius von Haast explored the area at the head of Lakes Tekapo, Pukaki and Ōhau in 1862, collecting specimens, making maps and writing comprehensive reports on his observations, and, starting in 1867, surveyor Edward Sealy explored many glaciers.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Many of the peaks, glaciers and other geographical features of the region were named by or for these early explorers, such as the Sealy Tarns track being named after Edward Sealy and the Mueller Glacier named after Ferdinand von Mueller.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Public appreciation of the mountains also grew as images of the area began to circulate.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Artists painted pictures, and from 1867–1870 Sealy photographed the Mount Cook region.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1873 the then Governor of New Zealand, Sir George Bowen, visited the Mount Cook region, thereby further raising the profile of the area.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Parts of Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park were first set aside as a recreation reserve in 1885, and the national park was established in October 1953.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1990, the park (along with Westland Tai Poutini, Mount Aspiring and Fiordland National Parks) became part of the Te Wahipounamu World Heritage Site, the first place in New Zealand to attain World Heritage Status.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Following the settlement between Ngāi Tahu and the Crown in October 1998, a number of South Island place names were amended by the Ngāi Tahu Claims Settlement Act 1998 to incorporate their Māori names.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The name of the mountain village and national park were officially changed from Mount Cook to Aoraki / Mount Cook.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Efforts to protect the alpine environment began in the 19th century.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] A petition addressed to James Sutter, a member of Parliament, was circulated in November 1884, requesting that the Government protect the alpine region around Aoraki / Mount Cook.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Petitioners were concerned that stock grazing and burn-offs were destroying the native bush and vegetation of the area.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The petitioners suggested that Frank Huddleston, who had recently bought land at the base of the Mueller Glacier and was building the Hermitage, be appointed as a ranger to oversee the area.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In January 1885 the Hooker and Mueller Valleys were gazetted as the Hooker Glacier Recreation Reserve.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1887 the Government permanently reserved an area of 97,800 acres of the Tasman Valley above the Mueller Valley confluence, which was known as the Tasman Recreation Reserve or Tasman Park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Hooker Glacier reserve was expanded in 1890, becoming the 38,000-acre Aorangi Domain.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1953, Tasman Park and Aorangi Domain became the Mount Cook National Park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park as established covered 151,780 acres (614.2 km2) of the Southern Alps, including the Mueller, Hooker, and Tasman glaciers and the eastern slopes of Aoraki / Mount Cook and Mount Tasman.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park is managed by the Department Of Conservation and Ngāi Tahu, the iwi who hold *mana whenua* status of the land.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park stretches for about 60 km (37 mi) along the southwest–northeast direction of the Southern Alps, covering 722 km2 (279 sq mi) on the south-eastern side of the main spine of the Alps.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Of New Zealand's 20 peaks over 3,000 m (9,800 ft), all except Mount Aspiring / Tititea lie within the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] These include New Zealand's highest mountain, Aoraki / Mount Cook, at 3,724 m (12,218 ft).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Other prominent peaks in or nearby the national park include Mount Tasman, Mount Hicks, Mount Sefton and Mount Elie de Beaumont.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] At the end of the most recent ice age around 13,000 years ago, numerous glaciers were tributaries of a much larger glacier covering all of Hooker Tasman Valleys in hundreds of metres of ice.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] This glacier was about 85 km (53 mi) long and reached beyond the southern end of today's Lake Pukaki, up to 40 km (25 mi) south of Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] As the glacier retreated, it filled the hollowed-out valleys with rocks and gravel, leaving behind the flat-bottomed U-shaped valleys seen today.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Moraines left behind by the glacier's retreat can be seen in the valleys.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Glaciers cover 40% of the park area, notably the Tasman Glacier in the Tasman Valley east of Aoraki / Mount Cook which is the largest glacier in New Zealand.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] A majority of glaciers in New Zealand lie within Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park, such as the Tasman Glacier, Hooker Glacier, Murchison Glacier and Mueller Glacier, while further north in the park lie the Godley Glacier, Classen Glacier, Grey Glacier and Maud Glacier.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] All of these glaciers terminate at proglacial lakes formed in recent decades due to a sustained period of shrinking.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tasman Lake and Hooker Lake are easily accessible via walking tracks and are the only two of these lakes that have official names.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tasman Lake is the largest of the proglacial lakes.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Taking a boat tour among the icebergs on the Tasman Lake is a popular tourist activity.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Temperatures in Mount Cook Village range between extremes of −13 °C (9 °F) to 32 °C (90 °F), and typically fall just over 1 °C (34 °F) for every 200 metres (660 ft) of additional altitude.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Rainfall is similarly variable, with the driest months receiving around 300 mm (12 in) precipitation, but recorded maxima are 537 mm (21.1 in) in one day and 1,447 mm (57.0 in) in a single month.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] During the coldest months of the year, Mueller Glacier Lake, Hooker Lake, and Tasman Lake usually freeze over, at least partially.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The weather conditions in the park, in particular at higher altitudes, can be unpredictable and change rapidly.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Southern Alps lie along a geological plate boundary, with the Pacific Plate to the southeast pushing westward and colliding with the northward-moving Indo-Australian Plate to the northwest.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook lies in the centre of the Alpine Fault, a 600 km (370 mi) long active fault formed by the plate boundary, which has ruptured four times in the last 900 years.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Over the last 45 million years, the collision of the two tectonic plates has pushed up a 25 km thickness of rocks on the Pacific Plate to form the Southern Alps.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Extreme temperatures and high precipitation work to shatter surface rock, leading to erosion down the steep slopes.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In December 1991, an avalanche of 10 million cubic metres of snow and rock caused 10 metres to be lost off the top of Aoraki / Mount Cook.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Two decades of erosion of the ice cap exposed after this collapse reduced the height by another 30 m to 3,724 m, as revealed by GPS data from a University of Otago climbing expedition in November 2013.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] There are two main rock types in the Southern Alps: sedimentary sandstones and metamorphic schists.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The sandstones are greywacke and argillite, mostly to the east of the Main Divide, whereas the schists are mostly to the west of the Main Divide.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Rock along the Alpine Fault has been warped and folded into complex layers with much shearing and fracturing.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Very few fossils have been found in the rocks of the national park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Parts of the Malte Brun range can be dated to the Permian Period by fossils found there in red argillite.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] More than 400 species of plants are found in Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park, including more than 100 introduced plant species such as the colourful Russell lupin, wild cherry, snowberries, and wilding pines.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Most parts of the national park are either at higher altitude or in the proglacial valleys such as the Hooker Valley and Tasman Valley, where the soil of the valley floors and moraine walls do not support forest growth.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] As a result, the only pockets of forest and native bush, such as silver beech and tōtara trees, can be found in the park are along the southern edge of the Hooker Valley and the lower slopes of Sealy Range.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The plant life in the majority of the park consists mostly of alpine plants.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] All of these plants flower in the warmer months from November to February – early in the season in the valley floors, and later at higher altitudes.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] At the highest rocks of Aoraki / Mount Cook, around 14 species of lichen have been found.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The native vegetation continues to be under threat by introduced plant species ranging from non-native trees through to lupins, broom and non-native grasses.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] These are mostly contained in the valley floors of the Tasman and Hooker Valley, since they are the most accessible parts of the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tutu, a poisonous plant, flourishes throughout the Hooker Valley during summer.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tutu is considered *taonga* by Ngāi Tahu.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] There are about 35 species of birds in the park including the kea, the only alpine parrot, Australasian Harrier (*kāhu*), silvereye (*tauhou*), a small omnivorous passerine bird, New Zealand falcon (*kārearea*), and the pipit (*pīhoihoi*).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The tiny New Zealand rock wren (*pīwauwau*), a threatened species, is the only permanent alpine bird in New Zealand.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Small insectivores such as the rifleman (*tītipounamu*) and the fantail (*pīwakawaka*) live in the low forest and scrub, along with small numbers of two larger birds, the kererū and morepork (*ruru*).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Introduced species such as finches and sparrows live throughout the bush near Mount Cook Village.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The black stilt (*kakī*), the rarest wading bird in the world, primarily lives in the braided riverbed of the Tasman Valley.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 2019, young black stilts raised in a hatchery were released near the Cass River and Godley River.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] European explorer Julius von Haast reported seeing kākā and piopio in the national park in 1862, however the piopio later became extinct.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park is home to many invertebrates, including large dragonflies, crickets, grasshoppers, 223 recorded moth species and 7 native butterflies.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The black alpine wētā, also known as the Mount Cook flea, is found above the snowline.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The jewelled gecko lives in the park but is rarely seen.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Access to the national park began as a rough track from Twizel along the western shore of Lake Pukaki to the Hermitage.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The road, now known as State Highway 80, was improved over time.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In the 1960s a major hydroelectric scheme was underway in the Mackenzie Basin.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] This required Lake Pukaki to be raised by 37 m (121 ft), which would submerge parts of the gravel road to the Hermitage, so a new sealed road was built and completed in 1975.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The highway ends at Mount Cook Village, with a connecting road leading to the White Horse Hill camping ground.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Another small road leads to a car park near Tasman Lake, the start of a short walking track and the Ball Hut Route.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] A pedestrian swing bridge was built over the Hooker River in the Hooker Valley in 1911, providing easier access to climbing routes.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Rodolph Wigley's Mount Cook Motor Co was formed in 1906 to provide passenger and mail services to the Hermitage from the railhead at Fairlie.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The first coaches held between five and nine passengers and the journey from Fairlie to the Hermitage took around seven hours, not including a meal break.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The service evolved into Mount Cook Landlines, which transported visitors to Mount Cook Village from Queenstown and Christchurch until 1989.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1989, the new owner of Mount Cook Landlines, Tourism Holdings Limited, scrapped the coach services and the *Mount Cook* brand.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In recent years, coach services to Mount Cook Village are run by InterCity and other smaller operators.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1920, following his success running a bus service to Mount Cook Village, Rodolph Wigley raised the idea of providing flights from Timaru and Queenstown to Mount Cook.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] A test flight took place in May 1920, with a plane circling Aoraki / Mount Cook but not landing, but nothing came of the idea.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The first landing in the Mount Cook area took place on 4 December 1934.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] White and a passenger flew a Spartan from Timaru, landing at Birch Hill Flat, 5 km (3.1 mi) southeast of Mount Cook Village.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Wigley's Mount Cook Tourist Company then built a small airfield, Mount Cook Aerodrome, at Birch Hill Flat.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] There is also another airfield, Glentanner Aerodrome, which is 20 km (12 mi) from Mount Cook Village.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Mount Cook Airline began scheduled passenger flights to the area in 1961.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In December 2019, Mount Cook Airline was merged into Air New Zealand and ceased operations.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Mount Cook company developed retractable skis for small aircraft, providing direct access to snowfields for skiers and sightseers.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The first ski plane flight using retractable skis took place in 1955.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Mount Cook Ski-Planes and Helicopters is now an independently operated company, offering landings on the Tasman Glacier.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Helicopters also provide access to the mountains for hunters and climbers.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Ski touring is also possible on the Tasman Glacier, the descent from the top to the bottom is about 19 km (12 mi).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The village contains a small visitor centre, housing and amenities for the staff of the hotel and motels and other support personnel.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The village has a small public primary school, opened in 1960, which is the only school in New Zealand situated inside a national park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1884, Frank Huddleston opened accommodation he called "The Hermitage" at a site near the Mueller Glacier, to cater for climbing parties visiting the area.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The hotel was later expanded, but was severely damaged by two floods in 1913.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Hermitage was rebuilt on a more elevated site, opening in 1914, but that building was destroyed by fire in 1957.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] It was rebuilt quickly, opening in 1958, and since then has been altered and expanded several times as tourism increased.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] A visitor centre in the village features interpretation exhibits about the area's natural environment and history as well as an artwork collection.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park attracted over one million tourists in 2019, a significant increase compared to the three hundred ninety-eight thousand people that visited in the 2016/2017 season.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tourism significantly decreased after the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park is a popular location for day hikes, sightseeing flights, heliskiing, hunting, kayaking, mountaineering, ski touring and tramping.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Department of Conservation, alongside Ngāi Tahu, administers all activities in the park, including the White Horse Hill camping ground.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Recreational helicopter flights and sightseeing planes operate in the national park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park also attracts astrophotographers and stargazers due to low light pollution in the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Mount Cook Village is the start of several walking tracks, such as the popular Hooker Valley track which is 10 km (6.2 mi) long (return) and typically takes three hours to complete.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] About 1800–2000 people a day walk the Hooker Valley track in the peak season.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Sealy Tarns is another popular track in the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] It is more challenging than the Hooker Valley track, and is nicknamed "The Stairway to Heaven" due to its steepness.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Guided walking tours are offered on some other tracks, and boat trips and kayaking tours for tourists take place on the Tasman Lake at the end of the glacier.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park contains 15 huts, mostly in alpine terrain.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The huts range from basic shelters to serviced huts, with the most accessible being Mueller Hut, which can be reached from Mount Cook Village within four hours.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In February 2024, the Department of Conservation reported that 250 people per day were using the track to Mueller Hut, mostly as day-walkers.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The large number of visitors led to the toilets at the hut nearing maximum capacity.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The track was temporarily closed to day-walkers so that those with a hut booking could still access and use the hut.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park is the starting point of the Alps to Ocean Cycle Trail to Oamaru.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The 300 km (190 mi) cycle trail was constructed from 2010 onwards by the New Zealand Cycle Trail project.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] As of 2016 the cycle trail still includes 15 km (9.3 mi) along public roads.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The peaks of the Aoraki / Mount Cook region have long attracted mountaineers.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] William Spotswood Green made the first notable attempt to climb Aoraki / Mount Cook.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Green travelled to New Zealand with two Swiss guides to make the climb, after seeing Sealy's photographs of the mountain at an exhibition in London.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The three men got very close to the summit before being forced to turn back.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] At a dinner in his honour after the climb, Green noted that climbing would be easier if huts were built in the mountains, as the huts would provide shelter and a place to store provisions, lightening the load of climbers.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] He also suggested that New Zealand set up an Alpine Club, leading to establishment of the New Zealand Alpine Club in 1891.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] After several attempts, the first successful ascent of Aoraki / Mount Cook was made on Christmas Day 1894, by Tom Fyfe, Jack Clarke, and George Graham.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In December 1910, Freda Du Faur became the first woman to climb Aoraki / Mount Cook, and in 1913 her climbing party made the first ascents of the Footstool and Mount Sefton.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Mountaineering on the Aoraki / Mount Cook massif is a hazardous activity.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1982, Mark Inglis and his climbing partner were trapped in a snow cave for two weeks.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Other mountaineering routes include crossing the Aroarokaehe Range via the Copland Pass, and the Mount Cook Range via the Ball Pass.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The area was the training ground for Sir Edmund Hillary.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] On the opposite side of the Hooker Valley, Mount Ollivier was Sir Edmund Hillary's first major climb in 1939.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Since the establishment of a tramping track to Mueller Hut, not far below the summit, Ollivier is now one of the most accessible mountains in the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Another mountain popular for mountaineers of intermediate skills is Sebastopol, the closest mountain to Mount Cook Village.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] At 1,468 m (4,816 ft) in height, it is only 750 m (2,460 ft) above Mount Cook Village, with the lower half of the ascent following the Red Tarns tramping track.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Sebastopol offers one of a few view points taking in both the Hooker Valley and the Tasman Valley.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] There are 15 mountain huts in Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park for the use of climbers and hunters.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Twelve of these are managed by the Department of Conservation, two belong to the New Zealand Deerstalkers Association and one, Caroline Hut, is privately owned by an alpine guiding company.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Another hut—Red Stag Hut—sits just outside the national park in the adjoining Te Kahui Kaupeka Conservation Park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Hooker Hut, built in 1910, is the oldest surviving hut in the national park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] It has been moved three times as the Hooker Glacier receded, then was removed and restored before being reassembled in a new location in 2021.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The oldest hut still in its original location is Sefton Bivouac, built in 1917.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In June 2012, an area of 4,367 km2 (1,686 sq mi) including Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park and the Mackenzie Basin was designated as the Aoraki Mackenzie International Dark Sky Reserve by the DarkSky International.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] At the time of the designation in 2012, the reserve was the largest in the world, and the only reserve of its type in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The night sky brightness in the reserve ranks at a level 2 on the nine-level Bortle scale.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 2018 the Department of Conservation drafted a management plan for the park to consider how land, water, flora and fauna, aircraft and visitors to Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park could be managed over the following 10 years.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] However, review of the plan stopped in February 2019 to consider the ramifications of a Supreme Court decision involving Ngāi Tai, an Auckland iwi, who argued that DOC should consider the Treaty of Waitangi when granting concessions for commercial activities on conservation land.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Supreme Court found that "decisions to grant concessions to third parties would need to include asking whether the concession opportunities should be preserved for the economic benefit of Ngāi Tai and whether there was any basis for the preferential grant of concessions to Ngāi Tai".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] DOC paused work on the management plan for Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park while it held discussions with Ngāi Tahu.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The formation of the draft management plan occurred at the same time as the number of visitors to Aoraki / Mount Cook Park was increasing dramatically.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Visitor numbers doubled between 2016 and 2019, reaching more than one million visits to Mount Cook Village, the gateway to the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Proposals to manage the huge number of tourists included a booking system, a park entrance fee, and a "park and ride" system to limit traffic in the village.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] A local Ngāi Tahu leader noted that Tourism New Zealand has been encouraging lots of people to come to the country without necessarily having the infrastructure in place".
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Department of Conservation had concerns about management of increasing quantities of human waste and litter in the village and in alpine huts, suggesting that visitors might be encouraged to take their litter away when they leave the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] A wide range of introduced animals are present in the park or in surrounding regions.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] These include stoats, red deer, possums, tahr and chamois.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Many of these animals pose significant threats to the flora and fauna of the park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1904, the Duke of Bedford gave five Himalayan tahr to the New Zealand Tourist Department.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The South Canterbury Acclimatisation Society released the animals at Governor's Bush in Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park in December 1904.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1909, another eight tahr were released in the same area, and the population increased.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tahr cause damage to alpine plants, leading to soil erosion, and from 1937 the government has attempted to control the spread and numbers of tahr.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Department of Conservation encourages hunting of tahr in Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1907, the Emperor of Austria presented the New Zealand government with a herd of eight chamois.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The animals were released in the Hooker valley near the Hermitage Hotel as protected game animals, and within a few years they had begun breeding and spreading along the length of the Southern Alps.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] By the 1930s chamois were acknowledged to be causing damage to the alpine environment, by eating native plants and by trampling vegetation and compacting the soil.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Protection was removed and control measures were created.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Today chamois can be hunted year-round in Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Research on lead toxicity in kea living at Aoraki / Mount Cook in the 1990s found that of 38 live kea tested, all were found to have detectable blood lead levels, 26 considered dangerously high.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Additional analysis of 15 dead kea sent to Massey University for diagnostic pathology between 1991 and 1997 found nine bodies to have lead blood levels consistent with causing death.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] After further testing in the 2000s found lead in kea, the Department of Conservation attempted to remove all sources of lead such as flashings and nail heads from buildings in Mount Cook Village.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Kea Conservation Trust has continued this work with funding from DOC.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] After extensive filming took place in national parks including Aoraki / Mount Cook for the *Lord of the Rings* trilogy, concerns about the possible effects of such activities on the environment were raised at a workshop in 2002.
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park has been used as a filming location for numerous films, including *Mulan* (2020), *Vertical Limit* (2000), *The Lord of the Rings* film series (2001–2003), *The Chronicles of Narnia* film series (2005–2010), and *A Wrinkle in Time* (2018).
[src:mount-cook-national-park/mount-cook-national-park] Minas Tirith, the capital of Gondor in the fantasy adventure film series *The Lord of the Rings*, was filmed approximately 3 km (1.9 mi) away from Mount Cook Village.
